This French-language blog post from Kompozite explores the concept of CO2 equivalent (CO2e), a critical metric for measuring and comparing greenhouse gas emissions. The article aims to help readers understand the importance of this standardized unit of measurement in climate science and environmental reporting. It likely explains how CO2 equivalent allows for a uniform way to quantify different greenhouse gases by converting them to a common scale based on their global warming potential. By using this metric, scientists and policymakers can more effectively track, compare, and communicate the climate impact of various emissions sources across different types of gases and sectors.
